Text Statistics
README & Code Documentation
Purpose
The Text Statistics program is a Go tool that analyzes a block of text and reports key metrics about it: word count, character count, letter count, punctuation count, and line count. It is built entirely with Gos standard strings and unicode packages — no external dependencies are required.

 Where It Can Be Used
• Writing tools — show word/character counts like a word processor
• Content moderation — analyze text composition before publishing
• Document analysis — quickly summarize the structure of large text files
• Typing/grammar apps — track punctuation and letter usage
• Educational projects — demonstrate text parsing and unicode handling in Go

Programming Language
Language: Go (Golang)
• Version: Go 1.18+
• Packages used: fmt, strings, unicode
• No external dependencies and no regexp required

 What Each Statistic Measures
Statistic
How Its Counted
Words
Split text by whitespace using strings.Fields
Characters
Total runes in the text, including spaces and punctuation
Letters
Characters where unicode.IsLetter is true (a-z, A-Z, etc.)
Punctuation
Characters where unicode.IsPunct is true (., ,, !, ? etc.)
Lines
Number of newline characters (\n) plus 1


 Full Code
package main

import (
    "fmt"
    "strings"
    "unicode"
)

func textStats(text string) (int, int, int, int, int) {
    words := len(strings.Fields(text))
    characters := len([]rune(text))

    letters := 0
    punctuation := 0
    for _, c := range text {
        if unicode.IsLetter(c) {
            letters++
        } else if unicode.IsPunct(c) {
            punctuation++
        }
    }

    lines := strings.Count(text, "\n") + 1

    return words, characters, letters, punctuation, lines
}

func main() {
    text := "Go is awesome."
    words, characters, letters, punctuation, lines := textStats(text)

    fmt.Println("Words:", words)
    fmt.Println("Characters:", characters)
    fmt.Println("Letters:", letters)
    fmt.Println("Punctuation:", punctuation)
    fmt.Println("Lines:", lines)
}

Line-by-Line Explanation

Package & Imports
package main
Declares this file as the entry point of the Go program. Every executable Go program must have package main.

import ( "fmt"  "strings"  "unicode" )
Imports three standard library packages:
• fmt — used to print output to the terminal
• strings — provides functions for splitting and counting substrings
• unicode — classifies individual characters as letters, punctuation, digits, etc.

Function: textStats
func textStats(text string) (int, int, int, int, int) {
Defines a function named textStats that takes a string of text as input and returns five integers — words, characters, letters, punctuation, and lines, in that order.

words := len(strings.Fields(text))
strings.Fields splits the text into a slice of words wherever whitespace occurs, producing something like ["Go", "is", "awesome."]. len() then counts how many words are in that slice.

characters := len([]rune(text))
Converts the text into a slice of runes (individual Unicode characters) and counts them. This is safer than len(text) directly, since that would count bytes rather than characters, which can differ for non-ASCII text.

letters := 0
punctuation := 0
Initializes two counters at zero, ready to be incremented as the text is scanned character by character.

for _, c := range text {
Loops through every character (rune) in the text, one at a time. The underscore discards the index since only the character itself is needed.

if unicode.IsLetter(c) {
    letters++
Checks if the current character is a letter (any alphabetic character, not limited to English). If true, increments the letters counter.

} else if unicode.IsPunct(c) {
    punctuation++
If the character was not a letter, this checks whether it is a punctuation mark such as a period, comma, or exclamation point. If true, increments the punctuation counter.

lines := strings.Count(text, "\n") + 1
strings.Count counts how many newline characters appear in the text. Since a single line of text with zero newlines still counts as one line, 1 is added to the result. Two newlines, for example, would split text into three lines.

return words, characters, letters, punctuation, lines
Sends all five calculated values back to whoever called the function, in the same order declared in the function signature.

main() Function
text := "Go is awesome."
words, characters, letters, punctuation, lines := textStats(text)
Defines a sample text string, then calls textStats and captures all five returned values into separate variables. The order here must match the order returned by the function.

fmt.Println("Words:", words)
... (and so on for each statistic)
Each line prints a label followed by the corresponding count, with fmt.Println automatically adding a space between them and a newline after.

Sample Output
Statistic
Value
Words
3
Characters
14
Letters
11
Punctuation
1
Lines
1


How to Run
• Save the code in a file called main.go
• Open your terminal in the same folder
go run main.go
The statistics will print to your terminal.

